In JavaScript, loops are used to repeatedly execute a block of code as long as a specified condition is true. There are several types of loops you can use:
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1) for Loop
The for loop is commonly used when the number of iterations is known beforehand. It consists of three parts: initialization, condition, and increment/decrement.

for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    console.log(i); // Output: 0 1 2 3 4
}
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2) while Loop
The while loop runs as long as the specified condition is true. It's useful when the number of iterations is not known in advance.

let i = 0;

while (i < 5) {
    console.log(i); // Output: 0 1 2 3 4
    i++;
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3) do...while Loop
The do...while loop is similar to the while loop, but it guarantees that the block of code is executed at least once because the condition is evaluated after the block is executed.

let i = 0;

do {
    console.log(i); // Output: 0 1 2 3 4
    i++;
} while (i < 5);

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
for...in Loop
The for...in loop iterates over the enumerable properties of an object. It’s primarily used to loop through object properties.

let person = {
    name: "Alice",
    age: 25,
    city: "New York"
};

for (let key in person) {
    console.log(key + ": " + person[key]);
}
// Output:
// name: Alice
// age: 25
// city: New York

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
for...of Loop
The for...of loop is used to iterate over iterable objects like arrays, strings, and other collections. It’s useful for looping through elements.
--------------------------------------------------
Example of for...of Loop with a Array


let numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50];

for (let number of numbers) {
    console.log(number); // Output: 10 20 30 40 50
}
----------------------------------------------------
Example of for...of Loop with a String

let text = "Hello, World!";

for (let char of text) {
    console.log(char);
}
// Output:
// H
// e
// l
// l
// o
// ,
//  
// W
// o
// r
// l
// d
// !

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                                                              control statement
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Breaking Out of Loops
You can use the break statement to exit a loop early and the continue statement to skip to the next iteration of the loop.

break Example:

for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (i === 5) {
        break; // Exits the loop when i is 5
    }
    console.log(i); // Output: 0 1 2 3 4
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

continue Example:
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (i % 2 === 0) {
        continue; // Skips the current iteration if i is even
    }
    console.log(i); // Output: 1 3 5 7 9
}

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                                                                    nested loop
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 <script>
        for (let i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    for (let j = 1; j <= 10; j++) {
        document.write(i * j)
    }
   
}

 
    </script>























